text: I didn’t mean progressive in the political sense. I mean that heightened transparency on the bureaucratic level is a democratic step forward for any government. I definitely have issues with the arrests of private citizens being fully public in perpetuity
author: jessmisener

text: The amount of transparency Florida grants the public into government proceedings is progressive, imo. I do think the access to arrest records of private citizens is the most questionable part of this law
author: jessmisener

text: So that’s why you see so many stories about crazy stuff going down in FL, which start as local stories then get picked up by like, the Daily Mail.
author: jessmisener

text: I'm sure scouring arrest records for "Florida Man" stories has been more than one Florida newspaper intern's full time job.
author: jessmisener

text: So if a local newspaper needs content, Florida Man stories are a gimme. A reporter can call the police department and ask for a full arrest report for any of those arrests, and almost always the police legally have to provide it. (Journalists in other states have it much harder!)
author: jessmisener

text: On my county’s website, for example, you can see everyone who was arrested in the past 24 hours with a click of a button. Mug shots, full names, charges, everything.
author: jessmisener

text: Florida has something called the Sunshine Law that gives the public *very* open access to public records. (It’s actually very progressive!) This includes government meetings minutes, documents, and... arrest reports from sheriff's offices and police departments.
author: jessmisener

text: This tweet is going around and as someone who grew up in Florida, I feel compelled to explain why it seems like there's so many *~crazy news stories~* coming out of there 24/7
